Regression on Cars Dataset¶

by Aleksander Partyga and Marian Nehrebecki

Introduction¶

In this project we want to show different machine learning approaches in a regression problem. The main goal is to built a model which will predict a price of a car, based on the given set of features. The dataset was downloaded from Kaggle and concerns set of more than 38 thousand cars that was scraped from the Belarusian listing website in December 2019.

The project can be divided into 2 main parts. In the first part we cover Exploratory Data Analysis and Data Preprocessing. We present graphically or numerically how every single variable is related to the price of a car and we draw preliminary conclusions about the effects of certain features. Additionally, we perform one-hot encoding and delete observations with missing data.

In the second part, after the data is prepared appropriately, we built three different types of models: Linear Regression, Regression Tree and XGBoost. We perform cross-validation, present some insights from the model learning process (for Regression Tree model) and build models with different set of parameters. At the end of each section we present how the model performed on the testing sample by measuring the size of the errors (with the Mean Absolute Error).

It seems reasonable that the variables:

  • readiness of the owner to exchange to car to other cars (is_exchangeable)
  • how long ago was this offer posted (duration_listed)
  • number of times the car has been upped (up_counter)

should not affect the price of the car. Let's drop them, which will help to avoid redundancy and overfitting problems. Let's now explore the correlations between the chosen numerical variables. Highly correlated (more than 0.7 / 0.8) variables are not desired in this case, as we want to avoid mulitcolinearlity problem.

Categorical variables¶

While exploring the categorical variables, I will focus on the groups in each category that are quite numerous (minimum number of observations will depend on how numerous the groups are). This is due to the fact that some of the variables have many categories and it would be hard to draw any conclusions from visualizing them all at once. Moreover groups with only a couple observations might be outliers, and a particular feature rather than an indicator of a clear pattern is an exception that should not be taken into account in case of extrapolating for a bigger sample.

Now the results are much better in terms of MAPE but worse in terms of MAE! This resulst indicate that using Mean Absolute Error is a better performance metric when the whole spectrum of cars prices is concerned. Therefore, to evaluate performance of models we will stick with MAE for the rest of this project. Lets try some more sophisticated modelling methods and see whether they will further improve the results.

 

Cross - validation results¶

We perform a 5-fold cross-validation to be sure that obtained results are stable. We use a function ShuffleSplit() that splits the data in a defined proportions (in case of our model it will be 4:1) and sample observations randomly. This way we can ensure that observations much different from each other (especially in terms of prices) will fall into each split. We do that in case the data was ordered in any way originally.

 

In [61]:
lin_reg_cval = cross_val_score(lin_reg, cars_new, prices_new, cv = ShuffleSplit(n_splits = 5, random_state = 13, train_size = 0.8), scoring = 'neg_mean_absolute_error')

Learning Curve¶

def ModelLearning(X, y):
    """ Calculates the performance of several models with varying sizes of training data.
        The learning and testing scores for each model are then plotted. """
    
    # Create 5-fold cross-validation sets for training and testing
    cv = ShuffleSplit(n_splits = 5, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 13)
    cv.get_n_splits(X)

    # Generate the training set sizes increasing by 1/6 of the whole training sample (~50k of observations)
    train_sizes = np.rint(np.linspace(1, X.shape[0]*0.8 - 1, 7)).astype(int)

    # Create the figure window
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(12,6))

    # Create three different models based on max_depth
    for k, depth in enumerate([5,10,15,20]):
        
        # measure time at the start of the loop
        start_time = time.time()
        
        # Create a Decision tree regressor at max_depth = depth
        regressor = DecisionTreeRegressor(max_depth = depth, min_samples_leaf = 10)

        # Calculate the training and testing scores
        sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(regressor, X, y, \
            cv = cv, train_sizes = train_sizes, scoring = 'neg_mean_absolute_error')
        
        # Find the mean and standard deviation for smoothing
        train_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis = 1)
        test_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis = 1)

        # Subplot the learning curve 
        ax = fig.add_subplot(2, 2, k+1)
        ax.plot(sizes, train_mean, 'o-', color = 'r', label = 'Training Sample')
        ax.plot(sizes, test_mean, 'o-', color = 'g', label = 'Testing Sample')
        
        # Labels
        ax.set_title('max_depth = %s'%(depth))
        ax.set_xlabel('Number of Training Points')
        ax.set_ylabel('Negative MAE (in USD)')
        ax.set_xlim([0, X.shape[0]*0.8])
        ax.set_ylim([-2000, -1000])
        ax.grid()
        
        # How much time single loop lasts
        elapsed_time = round((time.time() - start_time), 2)
        
        print(f'Learning rate of tree with depth {depth} was computed in {elapsed_time} seconds')
    
    # Visual aesthetics
    ax.legend(loc='best')
    fig.suptitle('Decision Tree Regressor Learning Performances', fontsize = 16, y = 1.03)
    fig.tight_layout()
    fig.show()

Learning rate of tree with depth 5 was computed in 90.93 seconds
Learning rate of tree with depth 10 was computed in 98.26 seconds
Learning rate of tree with depth 15 was computed in 100.88 seconds
Learning rate of tree with depth 20 was computed in 106.95 seconds

 

On the graphics above we see can learning curves of training and testing datasets corresponding to Decision Tree Regression model with different max_depth (maxium depth of a tree) parameter. 5-fold cross-validation was performed to get an accurate measure of the Mean Absolute Error across different samples of training and test data.

  • The model with max_depth = 5 is underfitted. As the number of training point grows it does not show any improvement in performance for both training and testing sample.
  • The model with max_depth = 10 is much better. It's performance increases with every iteration (5 thousand observations), for the testing sample, but for the training sample remains stagnant.
  • Models with max_depth = 15 and max_depth = 20 perform similarly well. One slight difference is the gap between the training sample and testing sample, as for the deeper regression tree the gap seems to be a little bit wider.

As max_depth is being optimized the min_samples_leaf is set arbitrally to 10 to dissallow forming leaves with just a few observations and make the model more general in its usage (hence, preventing the overfitting).

The following functions: ModelComplexity() and fit_model() will help to decide to choose model with optimal max_depth parameter.

 

Validation Curve¶

In [74]:
def ModelComplexity(X, y):
    """ Calculates the performance of the model as model complexity increases.
        The learning and testing errors rates are then plotted. """
    
    # Create 5 cross-validation sets for training and testing
    cv = ShuffleSplit(n_splits = 5, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 13)

    # Vary the max_depth parameter from 5 to 20 by a step of 2
    max_depth = np.arange(5, 20, 2)

    # Calculate the training and testing scores
    train_scores, test_scores = validation_curve(DecisionTreeRegressor(min_samples_leaf = 10), X, y, \
        param_name = "max_depth", param_range = max_depth, cv = cv, scoring = 'neg_mean_absolute_error')

    # Find the mean
    train_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    test_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)

    # Plot the validation curve
    plt.figure(figsize=(7, 5))
    plt.title('Decision Tree Regressor Complexity Performance')
    plt.plot(max_depth, train_mean, 'o-', color = 'r', label = 'Training Score')
    plt.plot(max_depth, test_mean, 'o-', color = 'g', label = 'Validation Score')
    
    # Visual aesthetics
    plt.legend(loc = 'best')
    plt.xlabel('Maximum Depth')
    plt.ylabel('Negative Mean Absolute Error')
    plt.xticks(np.arange(3, 21, 2))
    plt.ylim([-2000, -1000])
    plt.grid()
    plt.show()

The validationCurve() function has proven on the graphic above, that Decision Tree Regression model yields the best results on the validation dataset when the max_depth parameter is set to 15 (while the min_samples_leaf was arbitraily set to 10).

The results of this function have formally confirmed what was visible on the previous graphic. After performing 5-fold cross-validation we can conclude that the best results can be achieved with the maximum depth of the tree equal to 15.

The mean absolute error of around 1314 USD was achieved on the validation dataset (which was obtained as a part from training dataset to check the performance of tuned parameters. Final performance measure will be given on a test dataset.

Building trees was stopped tree number 417, so the best value of MAE (1016.5) was obtained for model with 413 trees.

 

XGB tuned model¶

Let's name a few most important parameters that are going to be tuned (whole list of parameters along with their definitions can be found in the offical documentation):

  • max_depth: maximum tree depth (opitmization process shown in the Regression Tree model before)
  • learning_rate (eta - boosting learning rate)
  • gamma: minimum loss reduction required to make a further partition on a leaf node of the tree. Increase in this parameter encourages pruning.
  • colsample_bytree: subsample ratio of columns when constructing each tree
In [92]:
params_1 = {
    'max_depth': [5, 8, 11, 14],
    'gamma': [0.5, 1, 1.5]
}

This time we perform only a 3-fold cross-validation, as tuning the XGBoost parameters is very computationally expensive. The parameters that will be tuned are defined in a dictionary called params_1. The combination of parameters will be drawn 5 times in a random fashion and then the fitting and measuring performance (MAE) of the model will be repeated 3 times in a cross-validation process.

In the first round parameters: max_depth and gamma will be tuned.

In the second round parameters: learning_rate and colsample_bytree will be tuned.

Lastly, the performance of the model with tuned parameters is going to be assessed.

In [93]:
%%time

ss = ShuffleSplit(n_splits = 3, test_size = 0.2, random_state = 13)

random_search = RandomizedSearchCV(clf_xgb_200, param_distributions = params_1, verbose = 3, n_iter = 5, scoring = 'neg_mean_absolute_error',
                                  cv = ss.split(cars_new, prices_new), n_jobs= 4, random_state = 13)

random_search.fit(cars_new,

Overall, best results on the test sample (MAE = 976.94) was achieved by following set of hyperparameters:
  • max_depth = 14
  • learning_rate = 0.1
  • gamma = 1
  • colsample_bytree = 0.8

To further increase the performance of the model one could increase the number of boosted trees, or try to optimize different paramaters. As this is very computationally expensive (hence, time-consuming task), we will not perform further optimization.

 

Conclusions¶

In this project we considered three different types of models: Linear Regression, Regression Tree and Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost). For each of the models we performed cross-validation to get an accurate performance measure on different samples of training and testing datasets. Moreover, the cross-validation technique was used to tune parameters for Regression Tree and XGBoost.

For Regression Tree, the Learning Curve was plotted that has shown how the performance of the model changes when additional observations are added (in relation to the various max_depth parameter values), and the Validation Curve was plotted in order to see how different max_depth parameters affect the final performance.

For the XGBoost, 3 models were compared in total. The first and second one set with default parameters differed among each other by the number of gradient boosted trees. Only the parameters of the third XGBoost algorithm were tuned and this final model achieved the most satisfying results in terms of Mean Absolute Error among all built models.
